HEPATITIS B AND C, BARBERS - PAKISTAN (ISLAMABAD) (02)
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Sat 16 Dec 2006
From: Prof Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: The GIDEON Database, Sat 16 Dec 2006 [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

Background data on hepatitis B and hepatitis C in Pakistan
----------------------------------------------------------
[Professor Steve Berger has abstracted the following data from the Gideon
database (<http://www.GideonOnline.com>), which are relevant to
interpretation of the subject matter of the ProMED-mail post entitled
"Hepatitis B and C, barbers - Pakistan (Islamabad) 20061215.3529". - Mod.CP]
Hepatitis B
-----------
WHO-UNICEF estimated that the percentage vaccine coverage was 63 per cent
in 2003 and 73 per cent in 2005.
2.97 per cent of children are seropositive by age 5 (Karachi).
Hepatitis B accounted for 5.5 per cent of acute viral hepatitis in Karachi
(1997 to 1998); 41.9 per cent in Lahore; 17 per cent among antenatal women
in Karachi.
HBsAg positivity surveys:
------------------------
3.6 per cent of children below age 12 in Islamabad (1995 to 1996)
1.8 per cent of children ages 1 to 15 years in Karachi
55 per cent of patients with chronic liver disease or hepatocellular carcinoma
2.28 per cent of blood donors (Karachi and Hyderabad)
2.56 per cent of healthy persons in Islamabad (1998 to 2004)
3.3 per cent of healthy blood donors in northern Pakistan
2.0 per cent of volunteer blood donors in Karachi (1998 to 2002)
0.6 per cent of gynecological patients in Quetta (2004)
8.3 per cent of Afghani refugees living in Balochistan (2003)
Hepatitis C
-----------
The nationwide carriage rate in 1997 was estimated at 2.40 per cent.
24 per cent of patients with chronic liver disease and hepatocellular
carcinoma are viremic; 1.18 per cent to 9 per cent of blood donors (1996).
Seroprevalence surveys:
----------------------
6.5 per cent in Hafizabad, Punjab (1997)
5.31 per cent of healthy persons in Islamabad (1998 to 2004)
15.9 per cent in Lahore
23.8 per cent in Gujranwala (Punjab)
3.26 [per cent] in Sialkot (blood donors, 1998 to 2000)
4.0 per cent in northern Pakistan (blood donors, 1996 to 2000)
0.44 per cent of children by age 5 (Karachi).
1.6 per cent of children ages 1 to 15 years in Karachi
68 per cent of hemodialysis patients and 10 per cent of controls in Lahore
(1999);
3.7 per cent in Islamabad.
4.8 per cent of antenatal women in Islamabad (2001 to 2002)
--
Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
[These data, though not exactly comparable, support the observation that
the incidence of hepatitis B and/or C infection is higher among those
employed as barbers and beauticians in Islamabad than in the general
population. - Mod.CP]
